Common Language Runtime or Runtime Manager
• the CLR is a runtime environment that provides services for executing .NET code,
• it helps for memory management, security, and exception handling.
• By providing these features, the CLR allows developers to focus on writing high-level
code without having to worry about the low-level details of system-level programming.
Managed Code and Unmanaged Code
• IF the code executes using CLR, then that is managed code. For ex: C#, VB.NET
• The code executes without CLR, that is called unmanaged code. For ex: JS, Html and so on
Common Type System
• The Common Type System (CTS) is a component of the .NET Framework
• It gives set of rules for defining, using, and managing types in .NET applications.
• it provides a common language for defining types that can be used across different
programming languages and platforms.
Some of the key features of the CTS include:
• Type safety: The CTS enforces strict rules for type safety, which helps to prevent
errors and improve the reliability of .NET applications.
• Inheritance: The CTS defines rules for how types can inherit from each other,
allowing developers to create complex object hierarchies and reuse code.
• Polymorphism: The CTS allows different types to be treated as the same type,
which enables developers to write code that can work with different types of
objects.
• Interoperability: The CTS allows different programming languages to
interoperate with each other and with the .NET Framework, making it easier to
develop and maintain complex applications.
Stack and Heap
A stack is a region of memory that stores method calls and local variables. The stack is used to
store short-lived data that is only needed while a particular method is executing. When a
method completes, the data on the stack is discarded.
A heap, on the other hand, is a region of memory that is used to store objects. The heap is used
to store long-lived data that is shared between multiple methods and objects. Objects on the
heap are dynamically allocated and are managed by the .NET runtime’s garbage collector.
One key difference between the stack and the heap is that the stack is faster to access than the
heap, because the data on the stack is organized in a Last In, First Out (LIFO) manner, which
allows the processor to access it quickly. However, the stack has a limited size and can only
store a limited amount of data. The heap, on the other hand, can store a much larger amount of
data, but accessing data on the heap is slower than accessing data on the stack.
void MyMethod()
{
int x = 10; // x is stored on the stack
int y = 20; // y is stored on the stack
int z = x + y; // z is stored on the stack
}
class MyClass
{
public int MyProperty { get; set; }
}
void MyMethod()
{
MyClass obj = new MyClass(); // obj is a reference stored on the stack, the actual object is
stored on the heap
obj.MyProperty = 42; // the property value is stored in the object on the heap
}
String –
• Strings are a special case in C# because they are reference types, but they are
immutable and stored on the heap.
• When a string is created or modified, a new string object is created on the heap, and
the reference to the new object is returned.
Here's an example:
string s1 = "Hello"; // s1 is a reference to the string "Hello" stored on the heap
string s2 = s1 + " World"; // a new string object is created on the heap containing "Hello World",
and s2 is a reference to this new object
Garbage Collector
• Garbage Collector automatically frees up memory that is no longer being used by an
application
• It helps to prevent memory leaks and other memory-related issues.
• The Garbage Collector runs in the background and periodically checks the managed
heap for objects that are no longer being used. When it finds such objects, it frees up the
memory they were using so that it can be reused.
• The Garbage Collector uses a technique called "mark and sweep" to determine which
objects are no longer being used. It starts by marking all objects that are still in use, and
then sweeps through the managed heap to free up any memory that is not marked.
// Force garbage collection every 1000 iterations
if (GC.GetTotalMemory(false) > 1000000)
{
GC.Collect();
}
.NET and .NET Core
.NET and .NET Core are both frameworks developed by Microsoft for building various
types of applications, including web, desktop, and mobile applications. However, there
are some key differences between the two.
One of the main differences is that .NET is primarily designed to run on the Windows
operating system, whereas .NET Core is designed to be cross-platform and can run
on Windows, Linux, and macOS.
Another difference is that .NET is a monolithic framework, meaning that it includes a
large number of libraries and dependencies. This can make it challenging to deploy
applications to certain environments, particularly in cases where only a subset of the
framework is required. In contrast, .NET Core is designed to be modular and
lightweight, allowing developers to choose only the components they need for their
applications.
Additionally, .NET Core includes several features and tools that are not available in the
traditional .NET framework, such as support for Docker containers and the ability to
build and run applications on non-Windows platforms.
Polymorphism
• polymorphism is a powerful concept in object-oriented programming
• It allows objects of different types to be treated as if they are the same type.
• This can be useful for writing flexible and reusable code that can work with multiple
types of objects.
public class Shape
{
public virtual void Draw()
{
Console.WriteLine("Drawing a shape...");
}
}
public class Circle : Shape
{
public override void Draw()
{
Console.WriteLine("Drawing a circle...");
}
}
public class Square : Shape
{
public override void Draw()
{
Console.WriteLine("Drawing a square...");
}
}
// Usage example
Shape[] shapes = new Shape[2];
shapes[0] = new Circle();
shapes[1] = new Square();
foreach (Shape shape in shapes)
{
shape.Draw();
}
SOLID principles
It’s a guideline for writing maintainable and scalable software in object-oriented programming.
• Single Responsibility Principle
• Open Closed Principle
• Liskov Substitution Principle
• Interface Segregation Principle
• Dependency Inversion Principle
1. Single Responsibility Principle (SRP):
• A class should have only one responsibility or job.
Example:
A Person class should be responsible for storing and retrieving information about a person
but its not responsible for performing any other tasks like sending emails or calculating tax.
2. Open-Closed Principle (OCP):
• A class should be open for extension but closed for modification.
• It means, class can be extended with new functionality, without changing the
existing code.
• This principle helps to prevent code from breaking when new features are
added.
Example: A Calculator class should be designed in such a way that new mathematical
operations can be added to it, without changing the existing code that performs the basic
operations.
3. Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP):
• A child class replace its parent class without affecting the correctness of the
program.
• This principle helps to ensure that code can be easily maintained and extended.
Example: If we have a Bird class, and a Penguin class that inherits from Bird, we should be able
to use a Penguin object wherever we would normally use a Bird object, without any problems.
4. Interface Segregation Principle (ISP):
• Child class should not be forced to depend on interfaces they do not use.
• This means that interfaces should be designed in such a way that clients only need to
depend on the methods that they actually use. This principle helps to prevent
unnecessary dependencies between classes.
Example: If we have an IMusicPlayer interface, and a VideoPlayer class that only needs to play
music, we should not include any video-related methods in the interface, as this would create
unnecessary dependencies.
5. Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP):
• High-level modules should not depend on low-level modules. Instead, they should both
depend on abstractions.
Example: If we have a Customer class that depends on a Database class to retrieve customer
information, we should use an interface ICustomerRepository between the two, so that we can
easily change the database implementation without affecting the Customer class.
Design Patterns
1. Singleton pattern
• Singleton pattern is a creational design pattern
• if we are creating multiple instances for the class, it could cause problems or lead to
unnecessary resource consumption.
• It helps to create only one instance of a class for entire system, also which can be
shared by other places.
• This can be useful for managing shared resources, such as database connections, log
files, or configuration settings,
For example,
In a multi-user application, multiple instances of a database connection class could
result in multiple connections being opened to the database, leading to increased resource
usage and potential conflicts.
To avoid, we can use Singleton Design pattern.
public sealed class MySingleton
{
private static readonly MySingleton instance = new MySingleton();
private MySingleton() {}
public static MySingleton Instance
{
get { return instance; }
}
}
2. Dependency Injection
• Dependency Injection (DI) is a software design pattern
• In which the creation of the object and binding of dependencies are done outside of
the dependent class.
• It allows us to develop loosely coupled code.
• So The purpose of DI is to make code maintainable.
•
• Dependency Injection (DI) is a design pattern in .NET that helps to manage the creation
and lifetime of objects, and to reduce coupling between different parts of the code.
• DI involves injecting dependencies into an object, rather than creating those
dependencies inside the object itself.
• This can make the code more modular, testable, and maintainable.
Controler:
• DI is typically implemented using a container
• It is responsible for managing the creation and lifetime of objects, and for injecting
dependencies automatically.
Object registration :
• Object registration is the process of telling the container which objects and services
should be available for injection.
• It involves registering a type(eg:class) with container, along with their dependency and
if required, configure options.
In order to use DI, objects should be designed to rely on abstractions rather than concrete
implementations.
This can help to reduce coupling between different parts of the code, and make it easier to swap
out dependencies later on.
public interface IMyService
{
void DoSomething();
}
public class MyService : IMyService
{
public void DoSomething()
{
Console.WriteLine("MyService is doing something");
}
}
public class MyController
{
private readonly IMyService _service;
public MyController(IMyService service)
{
_service = service;
}
public void DoWork()
{
_service.DoSomething();
}
}
// Object registration
var container = new Container();
container.Register<IMyService, MyService>();
container.Register<MyController>();
// Dependency injection
var controller = container.Resolve<MyController>();
controller.DoWork();
Service lifetimes
Services can be registered with one of the following lifetimes:
Transient:
• Transient lifetime services are created each time they're requested from the service
container.
• This lifetime works best for lightweight, stateless services.
• Register transient services with AddTransient.
• transient services are disposed at the end of the request.
Scoped :
• For web applications, a scoped lifetime indicates that services are created once per
client request (connection).
• Register scoped services with AddScoped.
• In apps that process requests, scoped services are disposed at the end of the request.
• When using Entity Framework Core, the AddDbContext extension method
registers DbContext types with a scoped lifetime by default.
Singleton
• Singleton lifetime services are created either:
o The first time they're requested.
o By the developer, when providing an implementation instance directly to the
container. (This approach is rarely needed)
• Every subsequent request of the service implementation from the dependency injection
container uses the same instance.
• Register singleton services with AddSingleton.
• Singleton services must be thread safe and are often used in stateless services.
Generic
Generic means the general form, not specific. In C#, generic means not specific to a particular
data type.
It is allowed us to create classes, structures, interfaces, methods, and delegates that can work
with any data type., without having to write separate code for each data type.
A generic type is declared by specifying a type parameter in an angle brackets after a type name,
e.g. TypeName<T> where T is a type parameter.
List:
List<int> numbers = new List<int>();
numbers.Add(1);
numbers.Add(2);
numbers.Add(3);
foreach (int number in numbers)
{
Console.WriteLine(number);
}
Dictionary:
Dictionary<string, int> ages = new Dictionary<string, int>();
ages.Add("Alice", 25);
ages.Add("Bob", 30);
ages.Add("Charlie", 35);
foreach (KeyValuePair<string, int> kvp in ages)
{
Console.WriteLine("Key = {0}, Value = {1}", kvp.Key, kvp.Value);
}
Generic Interfaces:
public interface IComparer<T>
{
int Compare(T x, T y);
}
public class Person
{
public string Name { get; set; }
public int Age { get; set; }
}
public class PersonComparer : IComparer<Person>
{
public int Compare(Person x, Person y)
{
return x.Age.CompareTo(y.Age);
}
}
List<Person> people = new List<Person>()
{
new Person { Name = "Alice", Age = 25 },
new Person { Name = "Bob", Age = 30 },
new Person { Name = "Charlie", Age = 35 }
};
people.Sort(new PersonComparer());
foreach (Person person in people)
{
Console.WriteLine("{0} ({1} years old)", person.Name, person.Age);
}
Delegate
• A delegate is a type in C# that represents a reference to a method.
• It is a way to treat a method as an object that can be passed as an argument, returned as
a result, or stored in a variable.
• We use delegates to create more flexible and extensible code, by allowing methods to be
replaced or extended at runtime.
public delegate T Transformer<T>(T input);
public static int AddOne(int x)
{
return x + 1;
}
public static string ToUpper(string s)
{
return s.ToUpper();
}
Transformer<int> intTransformer = AddOne;
Transformer<string> stringTransformer = ToUpper;
Console.WriteLine(intTransformer(1)); // 2
Console.WriteLine(stringTransformer("hello")); // HELLO
Here are some scenarios where we might use delegates:
Callbacks:
• If we want to execute a method when a particular event occurs, we can pass a
delegate to that method.
• For example, we might have a method that reads data from a file, and we want to
execute a callback method when the data is ready to be processed.
Asynchronous programming:
• In asynchronous programming, we use delegates to specify the method that
should be called when an asynchronous operation completes.
• This allows us to perform other tasks while waiting for the operation to
complete.
Lazy Type
• In C#, the Lazy<T> type is used to defer the creation of an object until it is needed,
and to ensure that only one instance of the object is created.
• This can be useful for improving performance and reducing memory usage in
applications that have expensive or resource-intensive initialization procedures.
• particularly useful when working with objects that are not needed immediately,
or that are created infrequently.
• The Lazy<T> type has a constructor that takes a delegate that will be used to
create the object when it is needed.
Lazy<MyClass> lazyObj = new Lazy<MyClass>(() => new MyClass());
In this example, a new Lazy<MyClass> object is created using a lambda expression that
creates a new instance of the MyClass class. The lambda expression will only be executed
the first time the Value property of the lazyObj object is accessed.
To access the underlying object, you can use the Value property of the Lazy<T> object.
Here's an example:
MyClass obj = lazyObj.Value;
The Lazy<T> type also provides a number of other properties and methods that can be
used to control the behavior of the lazy initialization process, such as
• IsValueCreated, which returns true if the underlying object has been created
• ForceInitialize, which forces the initialization of the underlying object.
? and ??
The ? and ?? symbols in C# are used to handle null values and provide default values.
The ? symbol is used to create nullable types, which are value types that can have a
value of null. For example, you can create a nullable integer like this:
int? nullableInt = null;
The ?? operator is used to provide a default value for a nullable type or other expression
that might be null. It has the following syntax:
expression1 ?? expression2
If expression1 is not null, then it is returned. If it is null, then expression2 is returned
instead. For example:
int? nullableInt = null;
int nonNullInt = nullableInt ?? 42;
In this case, nullableInt is null, so the value of nonNullInt is set to the default value of 42.
The ?? operator can also be used with non-nullable types, by providing a default value
that is of the same type. For example:
string str = null;
string nonNullStr = str ?? "default";
In this case, str is null, so the value of nonNullStr is set to the default value of "default".
IEnumerator and IEnumerable
• IEnumerable is an interface that defines a single method called GetEnumerator(), which
returns an IEnumerator object that can be used to iterate over the elements of a
collection.
• A class that implements IEnumerable must provide an implementation of
GetEnumerator() that returns an IEnumerator object.
class MyCollection : IEnumerable
{
private int[] _data = { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 };
public IEnumerator GetEnumerator()
{
return new MyEnumerator(_data);
}
}
• IEnumerator is an interface that defines three methods: MoveNext(), Reset(), and
Current.
• An object that implements IEnumerator represents the state of an iteration over a
collection
• Provide way to move next element, reset the iterator and get the current element
class MyEnumerator : IEnumerator
{
private int[] _data;
private int _position = -1;
public MyEnumerator(int[] data)
{
_data = data;
}
public bool MoveNext()
{
_position++;
return _position < _data.Length;
}
public void Reset()
{
_position = -1;
}
public object Current
{
get { return _data[_position]; }
}
}
static void Main(string[] args)
{
List<string> Month = new List<string>();
Month.Add("January");
Month.Add("February");
Month.Add("March");
Month.Add("April");
Month.Add("May");
Month.Add("June");
Month.Add("July");
Month.Add("August");
Month.Add("September");
Month.Add("October");
Month.Add("November");
Month.Add("December");
}
//create IEnumerable of string
IEnumerable<string> iEnumerableOfString = (IEnumerable<string>)Month;
//If we want to retrieve all the items from this IEnumerable object, we can use a foreach loop.
foreach(string AllMonths in iEnumerableOfString)
{
Console.WriteLine(AllMonths);
}
//Create IEnumerator of string.
IEnumerator<string> iEnumeratorOfString = Month.GetEnumerator();//to convert list into
IEnumerator we can invoke the GetEnumerator method
//To retrieve all the items from the above IEnumerator object, we cannot use foreach loop instead
of that we need to invoke MoveNext() Boolean method.
while(iEnumeratorOfString.MoveNext())
{
Console.WriteLine(iEnumeratorOfString.Current);
}

value types and reference types in C#
value types and reference types are used to store and manipulate data
Value types:
• Value types are stored directly in memory and represent a single value.
• When a value type is assigned to a new variable, a copy of the value is made.
int x = 5;
int y = x;
y = 10;
Console.WriteLine(x); // Output: 5
Console.WriteLine(y); // Output: 10
Reference types:
• Reference types store a reference to an object in memory, rather than the object
itself.
• Examples of reference types include string, object, and classes.
• When a reference type is assigned to a new variable, a reference to the same
object is made, rather than a copy of the object.
Understanding the difference between value types and reference types can impact
performance in several ways:
• Value types are generally more efficient to pass around and manipulate, because
they are stored directly in memory.
• Reference types, on the other hand, require additional memory overhead to store
the reference to the object.
• Passing value types as parameters to methods can also be more efficient, because
a copy of the value can be made and passed to the method, rather than passing a
reference to an object in memory.
• However, in some cases, using reference types can be more efficient, such as
when working with large objects that would be inefficient to copy.
Overall, understanding the difference between value types and reference types is
important for writing efficient and performant C# code.
Structs
public struct Point
{
public int X { get; set; }
public int Y { get; set; }
public Point(int x, int y)
{
X = x;
Y = y;
}
public void Move(int dx, int dy)
{
X += dx;
Y += dy;
}
}
Structs are similar to classes in many ways, but they have a few important differences:
• Structs are value types, means it copied by value when passed to methods or
assigned to new variables.
• Structs are stored on the stack, rather than the heap, so its more efficient in
some cases.
• Structs cannot have a default parameter less constructor or inherit from other
classes or structs.
• suppose we want to store the same information of multiple people.
• In this case, creating variables for an individual person might be a tedious
task. To overcome this, we can create a struct

Const vs Readonly
• const need to be defined at the time of assignment, while readonly field can be
defined at runtime.
• constants cannot change once defined but readonly field can be assigned a value
while declaration or in the constructor.
• Memory allocation not required for constants because it embedded into IL Code. but
readonly allocate memory because they are stored in heap.
public const int VERSION = 5;
Public readonly int VERSION = 5;
Implicit conversion and Explicit conversion.
Implicit conversion is a type conversion that happens automatically by the compiler. In
implicit conversion, the conversion from one data type to another is done automatically
by the compiler
int num1 = 10;
double num2 = num1;
Explicit conversion is a type conversion that requires additional code to be written in
order to convert a data type to another data type. Explicit conversion is also known as
type casting. Explicit conversion requires the use of a cast operator to convert the data
type.
double num1 = 10.5;
int num2 = (int)num1;

String and StringBuilder
• string and StringBuilder used to represent text data,
• A string is an immutable object, meaning that once a string is created, its value
cannot be changed.
• If we modify a string, it will creates a new string object.
• A StringBuilder, on the other hand, is a mutable object that allows you to
efficiently manipulate strings without creating new objects.
• A StringBuilder internally maintains a buffer of characters and appends new
characters to this buffer as needed.
• its more efficient when working with large strings or when concatenating strings
repeatedly
StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
sb.Append("Hello, World!");
sb.Append(" How are you?");
string s = sb.ToString();

What is an interface in C#
an interface is a contract that specifies a set of methods, properties, and events that a
class must implement. It defines the signature of the members, but not their
implementation.
public interface IAnimal
{
void MakeSound();
}
public class Dog : IAnimal
{
public void MakeSound()
{
Console.WriteLine("Woof!");
}
}
public class Cat : IAnimal
{

Virtual and Override
virtual and override used to define and override methods in a class hierarchy.
public class Shape
{
public virtual void Draw()
{
Console.WriteLine("Drawing a shape...");
}
}
public class Circle : Shape
{
public override void Draw()
{
Console.WriteLine("Drawing a circle...");
}
}
// Usage example
Shape s1 = new Shape();
s1.Draw(); // Output: "Drawing a shape..."
Shape s2 = new Circle();
s2.Draw(); // Output: "Drawing a circle..."
Abstract vs Virtual
• abstract method does not have an implementation in the base class but must be
implemented in a derived class.
• A class that contains one or more abstract methods must be declared as abstract as
well.
• A virtual method that has a default implementation in the base class, but can be
overridden in a derived class
• If a derived class does not provide its own implementation, the default implementation
in the base class is used.
Abstract and Interfaces
Abstract Class
• Abstract class come with abstract keyword, and we can’t create instance for that class.
• It contains abstract method or non-abstract method.
• Methods are partially implemented in abstract class or only it has a signature.
• Using Override keyword, child class implement or override the existing functionality of
the abstract class.
public class Shape
{
public virtual void Draw()
{
Console.WriteLine("Drawing a shape...");
}
}
public class Circle : Shape
{
public override void Draw()
{
Console.WriteLine("Drawing a circle...");
}
}
Interface:
• An interface is basically a contract—it doesn’t have any implementation. An interface
can contain only method declarations.
• Interfaces can contain properties and methods, but not fields/variables.
• Interface members are by default abstract and public.
• It defines the structure that a class must follow but it won’t provide any implementation
details.
public interface IShape
{
void Draw();
}
public class Circle : IShape
{
public void Draw()
{
Console.WriteLine("Drawing a circle...");
}
}
IShape myShape = new Circle();
myShape.Draw();
Method Overloading And Method Overriding In C#
• Method Overloading means creating multiple methods in a class with the same names
but different signatures (Parameters).
• Method Overriding means having two methods with the same name and same
signatures [parameters]; one should be in the base class, and another method should be
in a derived class [child class].

Partial Class & Partial Method
• partial class and partial method , it help us to split a definition into multiple parts,
but they have different use cases and semantics.
• partial class is a class definition will split into two or more parts, each defined in a
separate file or section of the same file.
• The parts of the class are combined into a single class definition at compile time.
• It allows developers to split a large class definition into multiple files for easier
maintenance and organization.
• partial method, is split into two parts, a declaration and an implementation.
• Declaration is defined in one part of the code and implementation defined in another
part.
• The declaration is defined in one part of the code, while the implementation is defined in
another part.

LINQ Query
• LINQ (Language Integrated Query) is a feature of C# that allows you to query data from
different sources such as arrays, collections, databases, and XML documents, using a
common syntax.
some common LINQ keywords with examples:
1. from - specifies the data source
int[] numbers = { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 };
var result = from n in numbers
select n;
2. where - specifies a filter condition
int[] numbers = { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 };
var result = from n in numbers
where n % 2 == 0
select n;
3. select - specifies a projection or transformation
int[] numbers = { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 };
var result = from n in numbers
select n * 2;
4. orderby - specifies a sort order
string[] fruits = { "apple", "banana", "cherry", "date", "elderberry" };
var result = from f in fruits
orderby f
select f;
5. group by - specifies a grouping of elements
string[] fruits = { "apple", "banana", "cherry", "date", "elderberry" };
var result = from f in fruits
group f by f[0] into g
select new { FirstLetter = g.Key, Fruits = g };
6. join - specifies a join between two data sources
var customers = new List<Customer> { ... };
var orders = new List<Order> { ... };
var result = from c in customers
join o in orders on c.CustomerId equals o.CustomerId
select new { CustomerName = c.Name, OrderTotal = o.Total };
7. let - allows the creation of variables within a query
int[] numbers = { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 };
var result = from n in numbers
let square = n * n
where square < 20
select new { Number = n, Square = square };
Parellel Process:
To perform the comparison of data in an Excel file with data in a database in parallel, you can
use a multithreading approach.
• we use the await keyword to perform the file reading and database querying operations
asynchronously.
• We then use the Task.Run() method to run the comparison operation in parallel.
• The AsParallel() method enables parallel processing of the data.
• Finally, we use the await keyword again to wait for the comparison operation to
complete before reporting the differences.
// Read the data from the Excel file asynchronously
DataTable excelDataTable;
await Task.Run(() =>
{
using (var workbook = new XLWorkbook("data.xlsx"))
{
var worksheet = workbook.Worksheet(1);
excelDataTable = worksheet.RangeUsed().AsTable().AsNativeDataTable();
}
});
// Query the data from the database asynchronously
DataTable databaseDataTable;
await Task.Run(() =>
{
using (var connection = new SqlConnection(connectionString))
{
var query = "SELECT * FROM Table";
var adapter = new SqlDataAdapter(query, connection);
databaseDataTable = new DataTable();
adapter.Fill(databaseDataTable);
}
});
// Compare the data in parallel
var differences = await Task.Run(() =>
{
var parallelQuery =
excelDataTable.AsEnumerable().AsParallel().Except(databaseDataTable.AsEnumerable(),
DataRowComparer.Default);
return parallelQuery.ToList();
});
await, Task.Run() and AsParallel()
await is a keyword in C# that is used with asynchronous programming to wait for a task to
complete before continuing execution.
Task.Run() is a method in the Task Parallel Library that creates a new Task object and starts it
on a new thread in the thread pool.
AsParallel() is a method in LINQ that enables parallel processing of data by dividing the data
into multiple partitions and processing them concurrently on multiple CPU cores.

Get data from SQL
Method-1
using System.Data.SqlClient;

Id=myUsername;Password=myPassword;";

{

{

}
}
reader.Close();
}

adapter.Fill(dataTable);

{
Console.WriteLine(row["Name"]);
}
}
SQL Data Insert
using System.Data.SqlClient;
string connectionString = "Server=myServerAddress;Database=myDataBase;User
Id=myUsername;Password=myPassword;";
string query = "INSERT INTO MyTable (Column1, Column2) VALUES (@Value1, @Value2);";
using (SqlConnection connection = new SqlConnection(connectionString))
{
SqlCommand command = new SqlCommand(query, connection);
//we have to use the below line , if it is stored procedure
//command.CommandType = CommandType.StoredProcedure;
// Set parameter values
command.Parameters.AddWithValue("@Value1", "Value1");
command.Parameters.AddWithValue("@Value2", "Value2");
connection.Open();
int rowsAffected = command.ExecuteNonQuery();
Console.WriteLine("Rows affected: " + rowsAffected);
}

USING Keyword
• The using keyword in C# is used to define a scope in which an object is used, and
automatically disposes of the object when the scope is exited.
• It is primarily used to ensure proper resource management and prevent memory leaks.
• When we are creating using block, C# compiler generates a try-finally block.
• try block contains the code within the using block, and the finally block disposes of
the object created within the using block.
Boxing and Unboxing
Boxing is the process of converting a value type (such as an int or a float) to an object
reference type (such as object or string). This is necessary when you need to pass a value type
as an argument to a method that expects an object reference type.
Unboxing is the process of converting an object reference type back to its original value type.
To Avoid Boxing and Unboxing, you can use a generic method that takes a type parameter T:
public void PrintValue<T>(T value)
{
Console.WriteLine(value.ToString());
}
The different types of tests
Functional Testing
• Unit testing:
• Integration testing
• System testing
• Acceptance testing
Unit tests
Unit tests are a type of software testing that verify the behavior of individual units or
components of a software application in isolation. The purpose of unit testing is to ensure that
each individual unit of code functions correctly and meets its requirements before it is
integrated into the larger system.
By writing unit tests, you can catch errors and bugs early in the development process and
ensure that each individual component of your software application is functioning correctly
before it is integrated into the larger system.
Integration tests
Integration testing is a type of software testing that verifies the behavior of different
components or modules of a software application when they are integrated and work together.
The purpose of integration testing is to detect defects that arise when different components are
combined and to ensure that the software functions as intended.
By writing integration tests, you can ensure that different components of your software
application work correctly when they are combined and can detect defects that arise when
different components interact with each other.
Functional Tests
Functional testing is a type of software testing that verifies whether a software
application behaves as expected and meets its functional requirements. Functional
testing focuses on testing what the software does, rather than how it does it.
Here's an example of functional testing in action:
Suppose you have a simple email application that allows users to send and receive
emails. The application has several functional requirements, including:
1. Users should be able to compose and send emails to other users.
2. Users should be able to receive and read emails sent to them by other users.
3. Users should be able to search for and filter emails based on various criteria,
such as sender, subject, or date.
4. Users should be able to delete or archive emails they no longer need.
You can write functional tests to verify that the email application meets these
requirements. Here are some examples of functional tests:
1. Compose and send email: This test verifies that users can compose and send
emails to other users. The test could involve entering text into the email body,
adding attachments, specifying recipients, and verifying that the email is sent
successfully.
2. Receive and read email: This test verifies that users can receive and read emails
sent to them by other users. The test could involve simulating the receipt of an
email, opening the email, and verifying that the contents are displayed correctly.
3. Search and filter emails: This test verifies that users can search for and filter
emails based on various criteria. The test could involve entering search criteria,
such as sender or date, and verifying that the search results are accurate.
4. Delete or archive emails: This test verifies that users can delete or archive emails
they no longer need. The test could involve selecting emails to delete or archive,
performing the action, and verifying that the emails are no longer visible in the
inbox.
End to End Testing
End-to-end testing is the process of verifying that an application works as expected from the
user's perspective, by testing the application across multiple layers and components. Here's an
overview of the end-to-end testing process:
1. Requirements gathering: The first step in end-to-end testing is to gather the requirements
for the application or feature being tested, including functional requirements, non-
functional requirements, and acceptance criteria.
2. Test planning: Based on the requirements, you would create a test plan that outlines the
scope, objectives, and methods of testing, as well as the tools and resources needed to
perform the testing.
3. Test case design: You would design test cases that cover all the relevant scenarios and use
cases for the application, using techniques such as equivalence partitioning, boundary value
analysis, and decision tables.
4. Test data preparation: You would prepare the test data needed for the test cases, including
input data, expected output data, and any test-specific data such as user accounts or test
databases.
5. Test execution: You would execute the test cases according to the test plan, using
automated or manual testing techniques, and report any defects or issues found during
testing.
6. Defect management: You would track and manage defects using a defect tracking tool or
process, including assigning severity and priority, triaging defects, and retesting defects
after they have been fixed.
7. Test reporting: You would report the results of the testing to the stakeholders, including
any issues or defects found, the coverage and effectiveness of the testing, and any
recommendations for improvement.
8. Test closure: You would complete the testing process by performing a post-mortem review
of the testing, documenting any lessons learned or best practices, and archiving the test
artifacts for future reference.
Overall, the end-to-end testing process is a comprehensive and iterative process that ensures
that an application meets the required quality standards and performs as expected from the
user's perspective. It requires careful planning, design, execution, and reporting, as well as
attention to detail and collaboration among all stakeholders.
Acceptance Tests
Acceptance testing is a type of software testing that verifies whether a software
application meets the acceptance criteria and the requirements of the end-users.
Acceptance testing focuses on testing the software from the perspective of the end-user
and ensuring that it meets the needs of the intended users.
Here's an example of acceptance testing in action:
Suppose you have developed a new mobile app that allows users to order food from a
restaurant. The app has several acceptance criteria, including:
1. The app should be easy to use and have a clear and intuitive user interface.
2. Users should be able to search for restaurants and view menus and prices.
3. Users should be able to place orders and make payments securely and easily.
4. The app should provide real-time order tracking and notifications to keep users
informed about the status of their orders.
You can write acceptance tests to verify that the mobile app meets these acceptance
criteria. Here are some examples of acceptance tests:
1. User interface test: This test verifies that the app is easy to use and has a clear
and intuitive user interface. The test could involve simulating common user
interactions, such as browsing menus and placing orders, and verifying that the
app responds appropriately.
2. Menu and pricing test: This test verifies that users can search for restaurants and
view menus and prices. The test could involve entering search criteria, browsing
menus, and verifying that the information displayed is accurate and up-to-date.
3. Ordering and payment test: This test verifies that users can place orders and
make payments securely and easily. The test could involve selecting menu items,
entering payment information, and verifying that the order is processed
correctly.
4. Order tracking and notifications test: This test verifies that the app provides real-
time order tracking and notifications to keep users informed about the status of
their orders. The test could involve placing an order, tracking its progress, and
verifying that notifications are received at appropriate times.
Performance testing
Performance testing is a type of software testing that verifies the performance, speed,
and scalability of a software application under expected or anticipated workload. The
goal of performance testing is to identify and fix performance issues before the
application is deployed in production.
Here's an example of performance testing in action:
Suppose you have developed a web-based e-commerce application that allows users to
browse and purchase products online. The application has several performance
requirements, including:
1. The application should load quickly and respond promptly to user interactions.
2. The application should be able to handle a high volume of user traffic without
crashing or slowing down.
3. The application should be able to handle a large number of concurrent users
without degrading performance.
4. The application should be able to process transactions quickly and efficiently.
You can write performance tests to verify that the e-commerce application meets these
performance requirements. Here are some examples of performance tests:
1. Load testing: This test verifies that the application can handle a high volume of
user traffic without crashing or slowing down. The test could involve simulating
a large number of user requests and verifying that the application responds
within acceptable performance limits.
2. Stress testing: This test verifies that the application can handle a large number of
concurrent users without degrading performance. The test could involve
simulating a large number of concurrent users and verifying that the application
remains responsive and stable.
3. Transaction processing testing: This test verifies that the application can process
transactions quickly and efficiently. The test could involve simulating a large
number of transactions and verifying that the application processes them within
acceptable performance limits.
4. Scalability testing: This test verifies that the application can scale up or down as
needed to meet changes in user traffic and workload. The test could involve
simulating changes in user traffic and workload and verifying that the
application can handle them without degrading performance.
Smoke testing
Smoke testing, also known as build verification testing, is a type of software testing that
is conducted to ensure that the basic functionalities of an application are working
correctly after each build. The purpose of smoke testing is to quickly verify that the
application is stable enough for more comprehensive testing.
Here's an example of smoke testing in action:
Suppose you have developed a new mobile app that allows users to create and share
short videos. The app has several basic functionalities, including:
1. Users can create a new account and log in to the app.
2. Users can create and upload short videos.
3. Users can view and share videos created by other users.
You can write a smoke test to quickly verify that these basic functionalities are working
correctly after each build. Here's an example of a smoke test:
1. Open the app and verify that the login screen is displayed.
2. Enter valid login credentials and verify that the app logs in successfully.
3. Create a new video and verify that it is uploaded successfully.
4. View a video created by another user and verify that it plays correctly.
5. Share a video and verify that the sharing functionality works correctly.
Different types of non-functional testing:
1. Performance testing: Testing the speed, responsiveness, and scalability of the
software under various load conditions. For example, load testing a web
application to see how it performs when multiple users access it simultaneously.
2. Usability testing: Testing how easy it is to use the software and whether it meets
the needs of its intended users. For example, testing a mobile app to ensure that
it has an intuitive user interface and clear navigation.
3. Security testing: Testing the software for vulnerabilities and ensuring that it
meets the security requirements of the organization. For example, penetration
testing a web application to identify and fix security vulnerabilities.
4. Compatibility testing: Testing the software to ensure that it works properly on
different platforms, browsers, and devices. For example, testing a web
application to ensure that it works on different versions of Internet Explorer,
Chrome, and Firefox.
difference between test plan and test strategy?
Test plan and test strategy are two different documents that are created during the
testing phase of software development. The following are the key differences between
test plan and test strategy:
1. Purpose: Test plan is a detailed document that outlines the specific testing
activities that need to be performed, while test strategy is a high-level document
that outlines the approach, goals, and guidelines for testing.
2. Scope: Test plan focuses on the details of the testing activities that need to be
performed, including the test cases, test scripts, and test procedures, while test
strategy focuses on the overall approach and methodology for testing.
3. Level of Detail: Test plan is a detailed document that includes specific
information about the testing activities, while test strategy is a high-level
document that provides a broad overview of the testing approach.
4. Timeframe: Test plan is created after the test strategy is developed, and it
focuses on the specific testing activities that need to be performed within a
defined timeframe. Test strategy, on the other hand, is developed at the
beginning of the testing phase and provides a framework for the testing activities
that will be performed throughout the project.
5. Audience: Test plan is typically created for the testing team and provides
detailed information about the testing activities that need to be performed. Test
strategy, on the other hand, is created for the project stakeholders and provides
a high-level overview of the testing approach.
Test suite and Test case
Test suite and test case are two fundamental concepts in software testing. Here are brief
explanations of each:
1. Test suite: A test suite is a collection of test cases that are designed to test a
particular software application or system. A test suite can include any number of
test cases, depending on the complexity of the system being tested. The purpose
of a test suite is to verify that the system or application is functioning as expected
and to identify any defects or bugs that need to be fixed.
2. Test case: A test case is a specific scenario or condition that is designed to test a
particular aspect or feature of a software application or system. A test case
typically includes input data, expected results, and steps to follow to execute the
test. The purpose of a test case is to verify that a specific aspect or feature of the
system or application is functioning as expected.
how will you measure test results?
Measuring test results involves evaluating the actual outcomes of testing against the
expected results. The following are some common metrics that can be used to measure
test results:
1. Test coverage: Test coverage measures the percentage of the application that has
been tested. This can be determined by analyzing the number of test cases that
have been executed versus the total number of test cases required to test the
application comprehensively.
2. Defect density: Defect density measures the number of defects per unit of code or
test cases. This metric can be useful in identifying areas of the application that
are particularly error-prone or require further testing.
3. Test pass/fail rate: Test pass/fail rate measures the percentage of test cases that
have passed or failed. This can help determine the overall quality of the
application and identify areas that require further testing or development.
4. Test execution time: Test execution time measures the time it takes to execute a
set of test cases. This can help identify bottlenecks or inefficiencies in the testing
process and optimize the testing approach.
5. Test automation coverage: Test automation coverage measures the percentage of
test cases that have been automated. This metric can help identify areas where
automation can be improved and reduce the time required for manual testing.
Localization testing and globalization testing
Localization testing and globalization testing are two types of software testing that are
related to internationalization.
Localization testing is a type of testing that focuses on ensuring that a software product
is culturally appropriate and properly translated for the target locale or language. It
involves testing the product's user interface, graphics, and text for compliance with
local cultural and linguistic conventions, as well as ensuring that the product can handle
different date, time, and currency formats.
Examples of localization testing include:
• Testing the user interface of a product to ensure that the translations are
accurate and culturally appropriate.
• Testing the product to ensure that it can handle different character sets, such as
Arabic or Chinese.
• Testing the product to ensure that it can handle different date, time, and
currency formats for the target locale.
Globalization testing, on the other hand, is a type of testing that focuses on ensuring that
a software product can operate in multiple languages and cultural contexts. It involves
testing the product's compatibility with different operating systems, browsers, and
hardware configurations, as well as testing its ability to handle different data formats
and character sets.
Examples of globalization testing include:
• Testing the product to ensure that it can handle different character sets, such as
Arabic or Chinese, across different platforms and configurations.
• Testing the product to ensure that it can handle different data formats, such as
date and time, across different locales and languages.
• Testing the product to ensure that it can handle different input methods, such as
keyboard or voice, across different cultures and languages.
Test centre of excellence?
A Test Center of Excellence (TCoE) is a centralized unit within an organization that is
responsible for promoting and ensuring quality in the software development and
testing process. The primary goal of a TCoE is to establish best practices and
standardize processes related to software testing to ensure quality and efficiency
throughout the organization.
A TCoE typically includes a team of experienced testing professionals who are
responsible for the following activities:
1. Developing and implementing testing policies, procedures, and guidelines.
2. Providing training and mentoring to testing teams across the organization.
3. Defining and implementing testing standards and best practices.
4. Conducting research and development to improve testing tools, processes, and
methodologies.
5. Establishing metrics and KPIs to measure testing performance and quality.
6. Providing testing consulting services to project teams throughout the
organization.
7. Ensuring compliance with industry standards and regulations related to testing.
A TCoE can help organizations to achieve the following benefits:
1. Improved testing quality and efficiency.
2. Standardized and consistent testing practices.
3. Reduced testing cycle time and costs.
4. Improved collaboration and communication among testing teams and other
stakeholders.
5. Increased transparency and visibility into the testing process.
6. Continuous improvement of testing practices and methodologies.
Parallel test execution
1. TestNG: TestNG is a testing framework for Java that supports parallel test
execution. It allows us to configure test suites to run in parallel, either by method
or by class. TestNG can also run tests in parallel across multiple threads, which
can help to further increase the test execution speed.
2. NUnit: NUnit is a testing framework for .NET languages such as C# that supports
parallel test execution. It uses the parallelizable attribute to specify which test
fixtures or test methods can be run in parallel. NUnit can also run tests in parallel
across multiple processes or multiple machines, which can help to further
increase the test execution speed.
3. Selenium Grid: Selenium Grid is a tool that allows us to run Selenium tests in
parallel across multiple browsers, operating systems, and machines. It uses a
hub-and-node architecture to distribute the test execution to multiple nodes,
which can significantly reduce the test execution time.
4. Jenkins: Jenkins is a popular continuous integration tool that supports parallel
test execution. It allows us to configure Jenkins build jobs to run tests in parallel,
either by splitting the tests into multiple test suites or by using multiple test
runners.
5. Azure DevOps: Azure DevOps is a cloud-based continuous integration and

Can you explain how you design a test automation framework using C#?
answer me in simple terms with example.
1.
Identifying the scope and requirements:
• We can identify the scope of our test automation framework as functional, regression, or
performance testing of a web application.
• Our requirements might include running tests on multiple browsers and platforms, using
a data-driven approach to test data, and generating test reports.
2.
Creating a project structure:
• We can use Visual Studio or another IDE to create a C# project with the necessary
packages and dependencies, such as the Selenium WebDriver and NUnit testing
framework.
• We can create a folder structure for test cases, test data, and page objects.
3.
Designing test cases:
• We can create C# test classes with methods to execute specific test cases, such as logging
in to the application or submitting a form.
• We can use Selenium WebDriver to interact with the web elements and validate the
expected behavior.
Here is an example of a simple test case in C# using Selenium WebDriver:
[Test]
public void LoginTest()
{
LoginPage loginPage = new LoginPage(driver);
HomePage homePage = loginPage.Login("username", "password");
Assert.IsTrue(homePage.IsHomePageDisplayed());
}
4.
Utilizing design patterns:
• We can use the Page Object Model design pattern to separate the page elements and their
methods from the test logic, making it easier to maintain and reuse the code.
Here is an example of a page object in C# for a login page:
public class LoginPage
{
private IWebDriver driver;
public LoginPage(IWebDriver driver)
{
this.driver = driver;
}
public HomePage Login(string username, string password)
{
driver.FindElement(By.Id("username")).SendKeys(username);
driver.FindElement(By.Id("password")).SendKeys(password);
driver.FindElement(By.Id("loginButton")).Click();
return new HomePage(driver);
}
}
5.
Reporting and logging:
• We can use NUnit test runner to generate test reports in HTML format, including a
summary of passed and failed tests, and detailed logs for each test case.
• We can also use log4net library to create custom logs and capture errors and exceptions
during the test execution.
6.
Integrating with continuous integration tools:
• We can use Jenkins or Azure DevOps to automate the test execution and to trigger the
tests on each code change or deployment.
• We can also configure the build pipeline to generate test reports and notify the team in
case of test failures.
First, we need to identify the scope and requirements of the test automation framework. This
includes identifying the types of tests we need to run, the test environment, the testing tools,
and the overall goals of the framework.
Next, we can create a project structure in C# that includes the necessary packages and
dependencies, as well as the core components of the framework, such as test cases, test data,
and page objects.
Once the project structure is in place, we can design the test cases using C# code, utilizing tools
such as Selenium for web testing, or other libraries for desktop and mobile applications. We can
also use C# to create custom test automation libraries to support specific testing requirements.
In addition, we can utilize design patterns such as Page Object Model, Factory Pattern, or
Singleton Pattern to make our test automation framework more efficient, maintainable, and
scalable.
We should also incorporate reporting and logging features to track the test results, including
any failed tests, and create automated reports for easy analysis.
Finally, we can integrate our C# test automation framework with continuous integration tools
such as Jenkins or Azure DevOps, to automate the test execution and to provide feedback to
developers in real-time.
Achieve parallel test execution?
Parallel test execution is a technique used in test automation to run multiple test cases
simultaneously, which can significantly reduce the time required to execute the tests.
Here are some ways we can implement parallel test execution:
1. TestNG: TestNG is a testing framework for Java that supports parallel test execution. It
allows us to configure test suites to run in parallel, either by method or by class. TestNG
can also run tests in parallel across multiple threads, which can help to further increase
the test execution speed.
2. NUnit: NUnit is a testing framework for .NET languages such as C# that supports parallel
test execution. It uses the parallelizable attribute to specify which test fixtures or test
methods can be run in parallel. NUnit can also run tests in parallel across multiple
processes or multiple machines, which can help to further increase the test execution
speed.
3. Selenium Grid: Selenium Grid is a tool that allows us to run Selenium tests in parallel
across multiple browsers, operating systems, and machines. It uses a hub-and-node
architecture to distribute the test execution to multiple nodes, which can significantly
reduce the test execution time.
4. Jenkins: Jenkins is a popular continuous integration tool that supports parallel test
execution. It allows us to configure Jenkins build jobs to run tests in parallel, either by
splitting the tests into multiple test suites or by using multiple test runners.
5. Azure DevOps: Azure DevOps is a cloud-based continuous integration and delivery tool
that supports parallel test execution. It allows us to configure test plans to run tests in
parallel across multiple test agents or test environments.
To implement parallel test execution, we need to ensure that our test cases are designed
to be thread-safe and do not have any dependencies on each other. We also need to ensure
that the test environment can support multiple concurrent test executions without impacting
the stability or performance of the system under test.
How do you integrate C# code with Selenium for test automation?
Integrating C# code with Selenium for test automation involves using the Selenium
WebDriver API to interact with the web elements and automate the testing process.
Here's a simple example of how to integrate C# code with Selenium for test automation:
• Install the Selenium WebDriver package: We need to install the Selenium
WebDriver package in our C# project using a package manager such as NuGet.
• Create a new instance of the WebDriver: We can create a new instance of the
WebDriver in our C# code, and specify the type of browser we want to automate,
such as Chrome, Firefox, or Edge.
IWebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver();
1. Navigate to a web page: We can use the WebDriver to navigate to a specific web
page, by providing the URL of the page we want to test.
driver.Navigate().GoToUrl("https://www.example.com");
2. Interact with web elements: We can use the WebDriver to locate and interact with
the web elements on the page, such as text fields, buttons, or links. We can locate
the web elements using various methods such as ID, name, class, or XPath.
IWebElement username = driver.FindElement(By.Id("username"));
username.SendKeys("myusername");
IWebElement password = driver.FindElement(By.Id("password"));
password.SendKeys("mypassword");
IWebElement loginButton = driver.FindElement(By.Id("loginButton"));
loginButton.Click();
3. Perform assertions: We can use the WebDriver to perform assertions on the web
elements, such as checking if a specific text or value is present on the page.
IWebElement welcomeMessage = driver.FindElement(By.Id("welcomeMessage"));
Assert.AreEqual("Welcome to Example.com", welcomeMessage.Text);
4. Close the browser: We should always close the browser window after the test is
complete.
driver.Quit();

Can you explain how to handle test data in a C# test automation framework?
answer me in simple terms with example.
In a C# test automation framework, we can handle test data in several ways:
Using configuration files: We can use configuration files such as XML or JSON to store test
data, and read the data from the file during test execution. This allows us to easily modify
the test data without modifying the test code.
string testDataFile = "testdata.json";
string testData = File.ReadAllText(testDataFile);
JObject testDataObject = JObject.Parse(testData);
string username = testDataObject["username"].ToString();
string password = testDataObject["password"].ToString();
Using external databases: We can store test data in external databases such as SQL
Server or MySQL, and use ADO.NET to read the data from the database during test
execution. This allows us to manage large datasets and perform complex queries on the
test data.
string connectionString =
"server=myServerAddress;database=myDataBase;uid=myUsername;pwd=myPassword;";
SqlConnection connection = new SqlConnection(connectionString);
connection.Open();
SqlCommand command = new SqlCommand("SELECT * FROM users WHERE
username='testuser'", connection);
SqlDataReader reader = command.ExecuteReader();
while (reader.Read())
{
string username = reader["username"].ToString();
string password = reader["password"].ToString();
}
connection.Close();
Using data-driven testing: We can use data-driven testing approaches to handle test data,
where we separate the test data from the test code and use external files or databases
to store the data. This allows us to run the same test case with multiple sets of data, which
can increase the coverage of the tests.
